Qualified import of GHC.Exts in generated code

We can import the identifiers with `#` supported by all GHC versions
unqualified from `GHC.Exts`, not expecting any clash with user code.

Identifiers that are only known in newer versions of GHC, in
conditional code, are referred to qualified, e.g. `GHC.Exts.foo`.

commit.message:
Add option `--numeric-version` and rededicate `-v` to future `--verbose`

Closes #250.
Doc: http:// links to https://
Readthedocs: add requirements.txt

Remove module `Sort`, use standard implementation

- `List.sort` and `List.sortBy` instead of `Sort.msort`
- `Set.toList . Set.fromList` instead of `Sort.nub'`

Optimise `preimage` using `mapMaybe`

Avoids throwing empty sets into the union.
Burning the bridges: remove #if for GHC < 8
Address `x-partial` warning of GHC 9.8, drop building with GHC < 8
gitignore TAGS file
Config file for readthedocs (soon mandatory)
v3.4.0.0: bump and CHANGELOG
Github Action to check for whitespace violations
Fix whitespace violations (like trailing whitespace)

Introduce strict-text and posn-strict-text wrappers and monadUserState-strict-text (#240)

This PR introduces the `strict-text` and `posn-strict-text` and  `monadUserState-strict-text` wrappers to allow working with Data.Text directly.

Implementation-wise we could do a bit better by using Data.Text.Foreign.takeWord8 and avoiding the intermediate list of bytes in a codepoint but this will do for now.

Squashed from these commits:
* Introduce strict-text wrapper
* Generalize posn string type
* Introduce `posn-strict-text` wrapper
* Add tests to `extra-source-files`
* Require `text` dependency for tests
* Don't run tests that require `text` dependency on older GHCs
* Introduce `monadUserState-strict-text` wrapper
* Update documentation with new `text` wrappers
* Remove trailing whitespace
* Incorporate Andreas' feedback

---------

Co-authored-by: Andreas Abel <andreas.abel@ifi.lmu.de>

Introduce strict-text and posn-strict-text wrappers and monadUserState-strict-text (#240)

This PR introduces the `strict-text` and `posn-strict-text` and  `monadUserState-strict-text` wrappers to allow working with Data.Text directly.

Implementation-wise we could do a bit better by using Data.Text.Foreign.takeWord8 and avoiding the intermediate list of bytes in a codepoint but this will do for now.

* Update documentation with new `text` wrappers

* Incorporate Andreas' feedback
